🔹 Basic Concept
Data Growth  ───▶  Database Overloaded  ───▶  Need Scaling
🔹 Types of Database Scaling
                 Database Scaling
                        │
        ┌───────────────┴───────────────┐
        │                               │
 Vertical Scaling               Horizontal Scaling
   (Scale Up)                      (Scale Out)
🔹 1. Vertical Scaling (Scale Up)
✔ Concept:

Increase power of a single server

Before Scaling:
   [ DB Server ]

After Scaling:
   [ DB Server ]
   (More CPU + RAM + Storage)
✔ Key Points:
Add CPU, RAM, Disk
Simple to implement
Limited by hardware
✔ Example:
Amazon RDS
Supports very high configurations (e.g., ~24TB RAM)
🔹 2. Horizontal Scaling (Sharding)
✔ Concept:

Split database into multiple smaller servers (shards)

        Large Database
               │
   ┌───────────┼───────────┐
   │           │           │
[Shard 1]  [Shard 2]  [Shard 3]  [Shard 4]
✔ Benefits:
Better performance
Easier management
Scales infinitely
🔹 Sharding Logic
✔ Using Hash Function:
Shard Number = UserID % N

Example:
UserID % 4

0 → Shard 1
1 → Shard 2
2 → Shard 3
3 → Shard 4
🔹 Resharding
✔ When Needed:
Data grows unevenly
One shard becomes full (Shard Exhaustion)
✔ Process:
Old Shards → Update Hash Function → Move Data → New Shards
✔ Challenges:
Data migration is complex
Downtime risk
Rebalancing required
🔥 Hotspot / Celebrity Problem
✔ Problem:
One shard receives too much traffic
      Users
        │
        ▼
   [Shard 2]  ← Overloaded (Celebrity)
✔ Cause:
Popular user / item (e.g., celebrity account)
✔ Solutions:
Distribute load across shards
Replicate hotspot data
Cache frequently accessed data
⚠️ Limitation of Sharding
❌ JOIN Operations become difficult
Shard 1   +   Shard 2   ❌ Complex JOIN
✔ Solution:

👉 Denormalization

Store related data in same table
Avoid cross-shard queries
